[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026680&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026680&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


I have a question about domain naming.  

Suppose our domain is as follows:

			edu
		      /
		  purdue
		/   |    \
	     cs    ecn    cc
	    / \     |    /
	   w   x    y   z

I am in the cs subdomain at host w.  To access host x, I can use the names
x.cs.purdue.edu or x (for which the resolver tacks on cs.purdue.edu since
it is my default domain.)

To access host y, I must use the name y.ecn.purdue.edu.

What I would like to do is access host y using the name y.ecn execpt that
since it has a '.' in the name, it is assumed to be a fully specified domain 
name.

If I were to imagine the above structure as a UNIX file system tree and
my current working directory is /edu/purdue/cs, I could access file y
with ../ecn/y.  Is there any way to do this form of relative addressing
in the domain naming scheme?

Paul Albitz
Computer Science Department
Purdue University

